  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 20.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "And the days which Jeroboam reigned were two and twenty years",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " [Bahr remarks that the exploits of this long reign find no mention in Scripture; the historian dwells exclusively on the sin, the consequences of which were of so much greater moment]: ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "and he slept with his fathers",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " [Jeroboam's end would appear to have been untimely. After his defeat by Abijah, we are told, \"the Lord struck him, and he died,\" which may either mean that he died by a lingering disease (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 21:18, 19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") or more suddenly (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 12:15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), but which certainly implies that he died \"by the visitation of God.\" I have suggested elsewhere (Homil. Quart. IV., p. 257) that the \"stroke\" was not improbably his son's death, which was at once so tragical and such a bitter foretaste of judgment to come. He may have \"warred and reigned\" (ver. 19) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "after",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " this event. He may also have steadily drooped to his grave], ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "and Nadab his son reigned in his stead.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " CHAPTER 14:21-31. THE REIGN OF REHOBOAM. - 1 Kings 14:20",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
